# Automated Legislation Reader - Cursor Rules

## Project Context
This is a Python-based legal research tool that retrieves Canadian legislation from CanLII, discovers related documents (regulations, amendments, case law), cross-references them using Anthropic's Opus 4.6, and produces a structured research package.

## Code Style
- Use Python 3.10+ with type hints
- Follow PEP 8 conventions
- Use descriptive function and variable names
- Add docstrings to all functions and classes
- Handle errors gracefully with try/except blocks and informative messages

## Architecture
- src/retrieval/ — CanLII API search and document retrieval
- src/discovery/ — Related document discovery (regulations, amendments, case law)
- src/analysis/ — Anthropic API cross-reference analysis
- src/output/ — Research package formatting (6-section template)
- src/pipeline/ — Agentic workflow orchestrator

## Legal Analysis Rules
- When analyzing legislation, always identify: definitions, obligations, penalties, and enforcement mechanisms
- Always map section-level relationships between Acts and their implementing Regulations
- Flag conflicts or gaps between related documents
- Use standard Canadian legal citation format (e.g., "Cannabis Act, SC 2018, c 16, s. 12(1)")
- Every claim must reference a specific section — no unsourced assertions

## Output Format
- Research packages follow a 6-section template:
  1. Executive Summary
  2. Document Inventory
  3. Cross-Reference Map
  4. Key Provisions Analysis
  5. Obligations & Implications
  6. Risks & Recommendations

## Git Commit Convention
- Always prefix commit messages with the Jira ticket key (e.g., "ALR-6: added search module")